Research Topic

Impact of randomization on social welfare and electoral system outcomes

Process

  • Part 1:
    • Dataset 1: In my theoretical society, there will be five candidates in the race for one elected position and fifteen voters. First, I will create a matrix where each voter randomly assigns each candidate a score between 0-100, thus using a score voting system. Using these scores, I will calculate social welfare outcomes through the Benthamite, Rawlsian, and Egalitarian winners.
    • Dataset 2: Using the same numbers from Dataset 1, I will adjust the scores for intensity of preference by dividing each score by the total number of points allotted by each voter and multiplying by 100. Essentially, the matrix will now demonstrate preferences such that each voter has 100 total points that must be distributed between the 5 candidates. I will recalculate winners for each of the social welfare functions. Next, I will calculate winners based on SMP, Borda Count, and Instant Runoff.
  • Part 2:
    • Dataset 3: In the second part of my code, I will randomly create fake profiles for each of the five candidates and analyze preferences from real people. I will gather preferences from six women that are students at Emory University, in Delta Phi Epsilon sorority, and were raised in the state of Georgia. I will recalculate social welfare functions and electoral system results based on their preference.
  • After gathering this data, I will compare the variability in results from computerized preferences and human preferences and analyze outcomes.

Adjusting for intensity of preference

#Now, each voter hypothetically gets 100 points that they have to distribute among 5 candidates based on their preferences
#Candidate preferences are now more comparable 
pref_sums = as.matrix((rowSums(prefs[,1:5])))
pref_sums.a = cbind(pref_sums, pref_sums)
pref_sums.b = cbind(pref_sums.a, pref_sums)
pref_sums.c = cbind(pref_sums.b, pref_sums)
pref_sums.d = cbind(pref_sums.c, pref_sums)

intensity_prefs = (prefs/pref_sums.d)*100
